Title:
PhantomKiller — Weaponizing Lenovo BootRepair.sys to Terminate Protected Processes (BYOVD)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
PhantomKiller is a Windows BYOVD proof-of-concept that abuses a legitimately signed Lenovo kernel driver (BootRepair.sys) to terminate arbitrary processes, including PPL-protected AV/EDR. The driver exposes an unrestricted device object (`\\.\BootRepair`) and an IOCTL (`0x222014`) that accepts a PID and calls `ZwTerminateProcess` without access checks or caller validation. This enables low-privileged users to kill high-privilege/protected security processes if the driver is already loaded, or attackers can load it themselves via `sc.exe` and then disable defenses. The repo includes a compiled driver/PoC and references a full reverse-engineering write-up. It’s primarily useful for red teams and offensive security researchers studying driver abuse and EDR tampering, and for defenders to understand and detect BYOVD-based process termination.

Technical Focus:
- BYOVD (Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver) using a signed vendor driver
- Windows kernel driver IOCTL abuse (`IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL`)
- Insecure device object / missing DACL on `\\.\Device` interface
- Kernel process termination chain: `PsLookupProcessByProcessId` → `ObOpenObjectByPointer` → `ZwTerminateProcess`
- Killing PPL-protected processes (EDR/AV tampering)
- Driver loading via Service Control Manager (`sc.exe`, type=kernel)

Use Cases:
- Terminate EDR/AV processes prior to post-exploitation tooling deployment
- Validate/benchmark EDR self-protection against kernel-assisted termination
- Research and reproduce insecure IOCTL / device ACL patterns in third-party drivers
- Develop detections for suspicious driver loads and IOCTL-based process killing

Keywords:
BYOVD, BootRepair.sys, Lenovo PC Manager, signed driver abuse, kernel driver, IOCTL 0x222014, \\.\BootRepair, IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL, IRP_MJ_CREATE, DACL, ZwTerminateProcess, PsLookupProcessByProcessId, ObOpenObjectByPointer, PPL, EDR tampering, AV bypass, sc.exe, Windows x64, process termination, driver exploitation